definition.value: A behavior which is intended to communicate a falsehood, typically used with the purpose of deceiving someone.

A form of psychological manipulation in which the abuser denies the abuse ever took place, attacks the victim for attempting to hold the abuser accountable, and claims that they, the abuser, are actually the victim in the situation, thus reversing the reality of the victim and offender. This usually involves not just "playing the victim" but also victim blaming.
Misconduct which takes place online, usually (but not always) on the internet.

The Internet-based practice of researching and publicly broadcasting private or identifying information (especially personally identifying information) about an individual or organization. The methods employed to acquire this information include searching publicly available databases and social media websites (like Facebook), hacking, and social engineering. It is closely related to Internet vigilantism and hacktivism.

Doxing may be carried out for various reasons, including inflicting harm, harassment, online shaming, extortion, coercion, business analysis, risk analytics, aiding law enforcement or vigilante versions of justice.
The leather culture as it exists in the LGBTQIA+ community.
The leather culture as it exists in the gay male community.
The leather culture as it exists in the lesbian community.
The leather culture as it exists in the deaf community.
Conspiracy theories related to LGBTQIA+ persons.

A social movement which opposes what is referred to as "gender ideology", a term which does not have a coherent definition. Individuals belonging to the movement typically oppose the distinction between sex and gender, oppose the ability for transgender persons (especially children) to access appropriate medical care, oppose discussion of gender theory and studies in schools, and oftentimes hold other relatively conservative views, such as opposing same-sex marriage. The movement derives from Catholic theology beginning in the 1990s, but the protests which brought the movement to attention did not start until around 2012â€“2013.

An activity and performance art in which participants called cosplayers wear costumes and fashion accessories to represent a specific character. Cosplayers often interact to create a subculture, and a broader use of the term "cosplay" applies to any costumed role-playing in venues apart from the stage.
A type of cosplay (costume play) in which the person dresses up as a character of a different gender.
Crossplay in which a person who is female dresses as a character who is male.
Crossplay in which a person who is male dresses as a character who is female.
A costumed gender performance which plays with or parodies traditional gender roles, perceptions and issues by intentionally presenting a confusing gender expression.
A term used in Fiji to describe an identity similar to the Samoan fa'afafine, i.e. persons who are assigned male at birth who take on a more traditionally feminine gender role.
A Tok Pisin term used recently to refer to the traditional gender identity/role observed in Papua New Guinea.
A term used in Niue to describe an identity similar to the Samoan fa'afafine, i.e. persons who are assigned male at birth who take on a more traditionally feminine gender role.
A male-to-female cross-dresser who performs in a glamorous manner, especially one who performs at nightclubs and other entertainment venues.
A female-to-male cross-dresser who performs in a glamorous manner, especially one who performs at nightclubs and other entertainment venues.

A language that is marginalized, persecuted or banned. Language minoritization stems from the desire of large nations to establish a common language for commerce and government, or to establish homogeneity for ideological reasons.
A term used to describe a person who displays visible aspects of gender variance, evidenced by their appearance or actions, among other things.
Cissexism in which it genitalia or other body parts are equated with a particular gender, usually in the form of assumptive gender attribution.
The condition of being non-intersex.
A gender which has a certain prerequisite which may be unrelated to gender, such as one belonging to a particular culture or Indigenous group.
Examples of exclusive gender identifications include Two-Spirit and intergender, among others.
A parent or parents that are nonbinary.
A kind of questionnaire which elucidates aspects of a person's gender identity and/or one's relationship to their gender identity.
Abnormal communication most commonly seen between two internal organs, or between an internal organ and the surface of the body.
Fear or hatred of masculine women; fear or hatred of butch people.
Attraction towards young women; alternatively, attraction toward young virgin women.
Attraction toward elderly women.

A type of trolling or harassment that consists of pursuing people with persistent requests for evidence or repeated questions, while maintaining a pretense of civility and sincerity. It may take the form of "incessant, bad-faith invitations to engage in debate".
Social activism against LGBTQIA+ persons and communities including, most prominently, the opposition to legal rights for LGBTQIA+ persons and communities.
Social activism against transgender persons and communities including, most prominently, the opposition to legal rights for transgender persons and communities.

The name given to a set of religious beliefs and practices originating in the ancient Greek and Hellenistic world, as well as from the Thracians, associated with literature ascribed to the mythical poet Orpheus, who descended into the Greek underworld and returned. Orphics revered Dionysus (who once descended into the Underworld and returned) and Persephone (who annually descended into the Underworld for a season and then returned). Orphism has been described as a reform of the earlier Dionysian religion, involving a re-interpretation or re-reading of the myth of Dionysus and a re-ordering of Hesiod's Theogony, based in part on pre-Socratic philosophy.
Feelings of discomfort or distress related to an individualâ€™s gender identity in relationship to their sexual characteristics.
Feelings of discomfort or distress related to an individualâ€™s gender identity in relationship to their hormonal and/or biochemical makeup.
Feelings of discomfort or distress related to an individualâ€™s gender identity in relationship to their social experience or experiences.
Feelings of discomfort or distress related to an individualâ€™s gender identity in relationship to gender roles and their associated expectations.
Feelings of discomfort or distress related to an individualâ€™s gender identity in relationship to their sexual experiences or lack thereof.
Feelings of discomfort or distress related to an individualâ€™s gender identity in relationship to their gendered presentation or expression or how such presentation and/or expression is perceived.

Feelings of discomfort or distress related to an individualâ€™s gender identity in relationship to missed opportunities, different expectations, and/or lack of particular experiences due to their assigned gender and/or sex at birth.
Gender dysphoria which is managed using any of various tactics including isolation, dissociation, presentation in a hyper-masculine or hyper-feminine manner, etc.

A representation of the processes, systems, or activities in health care, including patient care, management and economics, theory, assessment, research and education; may be manipulated to demonstrate the effects that various actions will have on health care processes, systems, or activities; generally developed for understanding, analysis, improvement, and/or replacement of the process.
A model for LGBTQIA+ health.
A model for transgender health.

label.value: informed consent model for transgender health

definition.value: A model of transgender health which emphasizes informed consent in the process of providing gender-affirming treatments, rather than relying on outmoded and pathologizing diagnostic models of transness.
An outmoded and pathologizing model of providing gender-affirming care, which requires applying a diagnostic (typically in the form of a disorder) in order to provide care.
Ableism as applied from a medical perspective or within medical settings.
Advertising focused on health services and/or products or health care generally.
